# Day 5: Durable KV Snapshots

An in-memory checkpoint disappears with the process. The durable conversation
can always rebuild it, but replaying a long agent history delays the first token
after resume. Today you will persist K/V as a validated acceleration artifact.

## The Event Log Remains Canonical

A session directory contains two different products:

```text
session.jsonl              semantic user, assistant, and tool events
cache/metadata.json        snapshot identity and logical layout
cache/tensors.npz          compact live K/V pages
```

The event log is portable and authoritative. The cache snapshot is optional,
large, and coupled to implementation details. Deleting or rejecting it must
only turn a warm resume into a cold replay.

## Versioned Snapshot Metadata

Validate at least:

- snapshot format version;
- model identifier and configuration hash;
- weight or revision fingerprint when available;
- tokenizer and chat-template hash;
- layer count, KV head count, head dimension, dtype, and page size;
- token IDs represented by the cache;
- per-layer logical length and block table; and
- a checksum for metadata and tensor data.

Reject unknown versions and mismatches with a useful cache-miss reason. Never
reshape incompatible tensors merely because their element count happens to fit.

## Compact Live Pages

The model-level pool may contain holes and pages owned by other sessions. A
snapshot must include only pages reachable from the saved session or checkpoint:

1. collect reachable page IDs per layer;
2. assign dense snapshot-local IDs;
3. gather each live key and value page once;
4. rewrite the saved block table to local IDs; and
5. retain logical tail lengths separately from physical page capacity.

On restore, allocate fresh pages from the current pool, copy tensor data, and
remap local IDs to the new physical IDs. On any failure, release all pages
allocated by the partial restore before falling back to replay.

## Crash Safety and Trust

Write into a temporary sibling directory, flush complete metadata and tensors,
and atomically replace the previous snapshot only after validation. An
interrupted save must leave either the old complete snapshot or no snapshot.

Treat snapshots as untrusted local input. Bound dimensions and file sizes before
allocation, reject path traversal, and use data-only formats rather than Python
object deserialization. K/V may also encode sensitive prompt content, so use the
same permissions and retention policy as the conversation log.

## Restore Policy

Disk restore is not always faster. A short transcript may prefill faster than it
can read a large K/V file. Implement a policy that can choose:

```text
cold replay | restore snapshot | keep resident
```

Start with an explicit CLI choice. Later, use measured snapshot bytes, prompt
tokens, storage throughput, and recent restore timing to make the decision.

## Exercise

1. Save and load a versioned snapshot for dense and paged caches.
2. Compact sparse physical page IDs and remap them on restore.
3. Reject a changed model, tokenizer, template, dtype, shape, or checksum.
4. Simulate interruption during save and partial failure during restore.
5. Prove that rejected snapshots fall back to transcript replay with identical
   greedy output.
6. Benchmark snapshot bytes, save time, restore time, and cold replay time over
   several context lengths.

